{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2017}} {{Infobox person | name = David Monn | image = File:David Monn office.png | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | birth_place = [[Fayetteville, Pennsylvania|Fayetteville]], Pennsylvania | residence = [[Manhattan]]<ref name="Departures">{{cite news | last=Rubinstein| first=Dan| title =Home Tour: Inside David Monn's New York Loft| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =''[[Departures (magazine)|Departures]]''| date =December 8, 2016 | url =http://www.departures.com/lifestyle/home-design/event-planner-david-monn-new-york-home-tour| accessdate =March 5, 2017}}</ref> | nationality = | other_names = | ethnicity = <!-- Ethnicity should be supported with a citation from a reliable source --> | citizenship = | education = | alma_mater = | occupation = {{flat list| *[[Event planner]] *Interior designer *Author *Artist }} | years_active = | employer = | organization = | known_for = Founder/CEO of David Monn, LLC | notable_works = | home_town = | title = | spouse = | partner = <!-- unmarried life partner; use ''Name (1950–present)'' --> | children = | parents = | relatives = | website ={{url|davidmonn.com/}} | footnotes = | box_width = }}
'''David Monn''' is an American [[event planner]], interior designer, author, and artist.<ref name="WP90">{{cite news | last=Roberts| first=Roxanne| title =With $90&nbsp;million raised, Trump's inaugural team is ready to party| newspaper =[[The Washington Post]]| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =| date =January 13, 2017 | url =https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/with-90-million-raised-trumps-inaugural-team-is-ready-to-party/2017/01/13/ddf5831e-d9be-11e6-b8b2-cb5164beba6b_story.html| accessdate =March 5, 2017}}</ref><ref name="Intro">{{cite news | last=Fiori| first=Pamela| title =David Monn Is a Master of Momentous Celebrations| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =''Introspective Magazine''| date =November 28, 2016 | url =https://www.1stdibs.com/introspective-magazine/david-monn/| accessdate =March 5, 2017}}</ref><ref name="Observer">{{cite news | last=Weiss| first=Zachary| title =White House Party Planner David Monn Released His New Book With an Epic Party| newspaper =[[New York Observer]]| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =| date =November 16, 2016 | url =http://observer.com/2016/11/white-house-party-planner-david-monn-released-his-new-book-with-an-epic-party/| accessdate =March 5, 2017}}</ref><ref name="WWD">{{cite news | last=Feitelberg| first=Rosemary| title =Friends Toast David Monn's 'The Art of Celebrating' at the New York Public Library| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =''[[Women's Wear Daily]]''| date =November 15, 2016 | url =http://wwd.com/eye/parties/friends-toast-david-monn-art-of-celebrating-at-the-new-york-public-library-10705977/| accessdate =March 5, 2017}}</ref> He is the founder and CEO of David Monn, LLC, an event production firm based in New York City.<ref name="Haute">{{cite news | last=Kotovos| first=Nicole| title =Architect of Style : David Monn| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =''[[Haute Living]]''| date =May 28, 2007 | url =http://hauteliving.com/2007/05/architect-of-style/98/| accessdate =March 5, 2017}}</ref><ref name="CNBC">{{cite news | last=White| first=Martha C.| title =Wedding Industry Preps for Bells to Ring After DOMA Ruling| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =[[CNBC]]| date =June 28, 2013 | url =https://www.cnbc.com/id/100852022| accessdate =March 5, 2017}}</ref> As part of the firm, Monn has been responsible for organizing and producing a variety of prominent events at locations like the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]], the [[New York Public Library]], [[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum|Guggenheim Museum]], among others.<ref name="NYTShopping">{{cite news | last=Fabrikant| first=Geraldine| title =Holiday Decorations in Gold| newspaper =[[The New York Times]]| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =| date =November 24, 2010 | url =https://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/25/garden/25shop.html| accessdate =March 5, 2017}}</ref><ref name="Bash">{{cite news | last=Laufik| first=Michele| title =David Monn on His New Book, Design Rules, and the Ultimate Event Job | newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =[[BizBash Media|BizBash]]| date =October 12, 2016 | url =http://www.bizbash.com/david-monn-on-his-new-book-design-rules-and-the-ultimate-event-job/new-york/story/32949/| accessdate =March 5, 2017}}</ref>
Monn designed a [[White House State Dinner]] for former United States President [[Barack Obama]].<ref name="Observer"/><ref name="NYTShopping"/><ref name="Preview">{{cite news | last=| first=| title =Shared, Lived, Felt: David Monn and the Art of Celebrating| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =Previews Inside Out| date =November 7, 2016 | url =http://www.previewsinsideout.com/shared-lived-felt-david-monn-and-the-art-of-celebrating/| accessdate =March 5, 2017}}</ref> Monn's most recent book, ''David Monn: The Art of Celebrating'', was released in November 2016.<ref name="WWD"/><ref name="Avenue">{{cite news | last=Gross| first=Michael| title =Celebrating the Art of Monn| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =''Avenue Magazine''| date =November 15, 2016 | url =http://www.avenuemagazine.com/hey-monn-who-bought-dat-party/| accessdate =March 5, 2017}}</ref><ref name="Page6">{{cite news | last=Mohr| first=Ian| title =Event designer goes all out for his book bash| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =''[[Page Six]]''| date =November 17, 2016 | url =http://pagesix.com/2016/11/17/event-designer-goes-all-out-for-his-book-bash/| accessdate =March 5, 2017}}</ref>
==Early life== Monn was born and raised in [[Fayetteville, Pennsylvania|Fayetteville]], Pennsylvania as one of six children. As a child, he showed an early interest in fashion design with hopes of attending the [[Parsons School of Design]]. In 1981 at age 18, Monn earned a job at Butte Knit, a clothing factory in his town that was a part of the Jonathan Logan Corporation. This job soon led him to New York City where he rented a studio apartment near [[Mindy Grossman]]'s. While in New York, Monn took up interior decorating for himself and his friends (including Grossman).<ref name="Intro"/><ref name="Haute"/>
==Career== Prior to beginning his event and interior design career, Monn worked in the jewelry business for 12 years. In 2003, Gayfryd Steinberg hired Monn as the event planner and designer for the Library Lions Gala at the New York Public Library's main campus. Since then, Monn has been designing events for a wide variety of occasions.<ref name="Intro"/><ref name="Sun">{{cite news | last=Gordon| first=Amanda| title =Authentic, Simple & Refined: A Night With David Monn| newspaper =[[The New York Sun]]| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =| date =August 14, 2008 | url =http://www.nysun.com/out-and-about/authentic-simple-refined-a-night-with-david-monn/83889/| accessdate =March 5, 2017}}</ref> In 2004, he managed the festivities for the grand opening of the [[Time Warner Center]]. The following year, Monn was responsible for the design of the Metropolitan Museum of Art's [[Costume Institute Gala]].<ref name="NYTInf">{{cite news | last=Trebay| first=Guy| title =Influencers Are Forever| newspaper =[[The New York Times]]| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =| date =June 26, 2005 | url =https://www.nytimes.com/2005/06/26/fashion/sundaystyles/influencers-are-forever.html| accessdate =March 5, 2017}}</ref> By 2007, his clients included the Guggenheim Museum, [[LVMH]], and the [[Metropolitan Opera]] (among others).<ref name="Haute"/> In November 2007, Monn designed the [[Frank Gehry]]-inspired Guggenheim International Gala at [[Pier 40 at Hudson River Park|Pier 40]].<ref name="Bash"/> He also designed the 100th anniversary celebration for the [[Plaza Hotel]] that year.<ref name="NYDN">{{cite news | last=Huguenin| first=Patrick| title =Event planner's the life of the party| newspaper =[[New York Daily News]]| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =| date =December 15, 2007 | url =http://www.nydailynews.com/life-style/event-planner-life-party-article-1.276028| accessdate =March 5, 2017}}</ref>
In May 2010, Monn designed the [[White House]] State Dinner honoring then [[Mexican President]] [[Felipe Calderón]].<ref name="NYTShopping"/> In November 2016, he released his book, ''David Monn: The Art of Celebrating'', which contains 360 pages of images and text about events he has planned and designed. The book's release date was marked with a party at the New York Public Library's main campus.<ref name="Intro"/><ref name="WWD"/> In January 2017, Monn designed an opening candlelight dinner for the inauguration festivities of President [[Donald Trump]].<ref name="WP90"/><ref name="NYTTrump">{{cite news | last=Bernstein| first=Jacob| title =How Anna Wintour's Longtime Party Planner Turned to Trump| newspaper =[[The New York Times]]| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =| date =January 18, 2017 | url =https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/18/fashion/inauguration-donald-trump-stephanie-winston-wolkoff.html?_r=0| accessdate =March 5, 2017}}</ref>
